{
  "title": "Observing WASM Targets Using FastAPI with Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This guide demonstrates how to set up and run WebAssembly (WASM) targets in a FastAPI application using Python 3.12+, enabling efficient and portable web development.",

  "key_points": [
    "Python 3.12+ is required for this tutorial due to its support for WebAssembly.",
    "FastAPI is a modern, fast (high-performance), web framework for building APIs with Python 3.7.x or newer.",
    "Emscripten is a toolchain that compiles C/C++/Rust code to asm.js and WebAssembly.",
    "We will use Emscripten's Pyodide, a Python environment in the browser powered by Emscripten.",
    "In this example, we create a simple FastAPI application that serves a WASM module compiled from C++ code."
  ],

  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "Python",
      "code": "```python\n# fastapi_main.py\nfrom fastapi import FastAPI, UploadFile, File\napp = FastAPI()\n\n@app.post('/wasm')\ndef wasm_upload(file: UploadFile):\n    with open('static/wasm_module.wasm', 'wb') as f:\n        f.write(file.file.read())\n```"
    },
    {
      "language": "Python",
      "code": "```python\n# main.cpp\n// ... (Your C++ code here) \n\nint main() {\n    // Initialize Emscripten and bind your C++ functions to JavaScript.\n    emcc -O3 -bind -s WASM=1 -s MODULARIZE=1 -o wasm_module.js your_cpp_source.cpp\n}\n```"
    },
    {
      "language": "HTML",
      "code": "```html\n<!-- index.html -->\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n  <meta charset=\"UTF-8\" />\n  <title>FastAPI WASM Demo</title>\n</head>\n<body>\n  <!-- ... (Your HTML code here) -->\n  <script src=\"wasm_module.js\"></script>\n</body>\n</html>\n```"
    }
  ],

  "version_notes": [
    "Pyodide has been updated to work with Python 3.12+.",
    "FastAPI is compatible with Python 3.7.x or newer."
  ],

  "caveats": [
    "Ensure you have Emscripten installed and properly configured for your platform before running this example.",
    "This example uses a simple WASM module, but in practice, you may want to compile larger projects using Emscripten."
  ]
}

